ChatGPT said:

The error StreamlitDuplicateElementId occurs when multiple st.plotly_chart elements are created with identical parameters, causing Streamlit to assign them the same internal ID. Streamlit requires each st.plotly_chart call to have a unique identifier when they have identical types and parameters.

🛠️ Solution: Add a key Parameter

Streamlit provides a key argument for its elements, which can be used to ensure each st.plotly_chart element has a unique identifier.

✅ Example Fix

Replace your existing st.plotly_chart(fig) with something like this:

python
st.plotly_chart(fig, key="unique_key_1")

If you're rendering multiple charts, make sure each has a distinct key:

python
st.plotly_chart(fig1, key="unique_key_1")
st.plotly_chart(fig2, key="unique_key_2")

The key argument must be a string and should be unique across all st.plotly_chart calls in your Streamlit app.

🔄 Dynamic Key Generation Example

If you're rendering charts inside a loop:

python
for i, fig in enumerate(fig_list):
    st.plotly_chart(fig, key=f"chart_{i}")

This approach ensures each chart has a dynamically unique key based on its index.

📚 Why This Happens?

  • Streamlit automatically generates an internal ID for each widget based on its parameters.
  • If two widgets share identical parameters, their IDs clash, causing this error.

🚨 StreamlitDuplicateElementId Issue: Plotly Charts Conflict

This error happens because Streamlit detects two st.plotly_chart components with identical internal IDs. This often occurs when:

  1. You're using identical parameters for multiple Plotly charts.
  2. Streamlit tries to auto-generate IDs but detects duplicates.

✅ Solution: Add Unique key Arguments

Each st.plotly_chart requires a unique key to differentiate them.

🛠️ Fixed Example Code

Ensure each st.plotly_chart call has a unique key:

python
import streamlit as st
import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

# Sidebar navigation
page = st.sidebar.selectbox("Select a Page", ["Home", "Data Dashboard", "About"])

if page == "Home":
    st.title("Welcome to the Home Page")
    st.write("This is the home page of your multi-page app.")

    data = pd.DataFrame({'Category': ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D'], 'Values': [48, 42, 64, 50]})
    st.write("Here’s the sample data for the Home page:")
    st.dataframe(data)

    fig = px.bar(data, x='Category', y='Values', title='Home Page Chart')
    st.plotly_chart(fig, key="home_chart")

elif page == "Data Dashboard":
    st.title("Data Dashboard")
    st.write("Here’s where your data visualizations and dashboards will go.")

    data = pd.DataFrame({'Category': ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D'], 'Values': [48, 42, 64, 50]})
    st.write("Here’s the sample data for the Dashboard:")
    st.dataframe(data)

    fig = px.bar(data, x='Category', y='Values', title='Dashboard Page Chart')
    st.plotly_chart(fig, key="dashboard_chart")

elif page == "About":
    st.title("About")
    st.write("This is an example of a multi-page Streamlit app.")

    data = pd.DataFrame({'Category': ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D'], 'Values': [10, 23, 45, 15]})
    st.write("Here’s the sample data for the About page:")
    st.dataframe(data)

    fig = px.bar(data, x='Category', y='Values', title='About Page Chart')
    st.plotly_chart(fig, key="about_chart")

🔑 What Changed?

  1. Each st.plotly_chart now has a unique key:
    • home_chart
    • dashboard_chart
    • about_chart
  2. This ensures no duplicate internal IDs for charts across different pages.

🧹 Clear Cache and Restart the Server

After making these changes, restart your Streamlit app:

bash
streamlit cache clear
streamlit run app.py

🛡️ Dynamic Key for Loops or Multiple Charts

If you're dynamically generating charts (e.g., in a loop), you can create dynamic keys:

python
for i, category in enumerate(['A', 'B', 'C', 'D']):
    data = pd.DataFrame({'Category': [category], 'Values': [i * 10]})
    fig = px.bar(data, x='Category', y='Values', title=f'Chart {category}')
    st.plotly_chart(fig, key=f"chart_{category}_{i}")

This ensures each chart gets a unique key.

🚀 How to Open a Different Streamlit Page (iris.py) in Your Browser

Streamlit serves one Python file at a time. To open a different file (iris.py) in your browser, follow these steps:

✅ Step 1: Stop the Current Streamlit App

  1. In your VS Code Terminal or Command Prompt, press:
    bash
    Ctrl+C
  2. This will stop the currently running app.py Streamlit server.

✅ Step 2: Run iris.py with Streamlit

  1. In your terminal, navigate to your project folder (STREAMLIT_PRACTICE) if you're not already there:
    bash
    cd path\to\STREAMLIT_PRACTICE
  2. Run the new file using Streamlit:
    bash
    streamlit run iris.py
  3. This will open iris.py in your default web browser.

✅ Step 3: Verify in the Browser

After running the command:

  • Your browser should automatically open a new tab pointing to:
    arduino
    http://localhost:8501
  • If it doesn’t open automatically, manually paste the address into your browser.

✅ Switching Between Files

  • To switch back to app.py, stop the server (Ctrl+C) and run:
    bash
    streamlit run app.py

📝 Pro Tip for Multiple Files in Streamlit

If you want multiple files (app.py, iris.py) to work as pages in one app:

  1. Create a folder named pages:
    STREAMLIT_PRACTICE/
├── app.py
├── pages/
│   ├── iris.py
  2. Streamlit will automatically detect the pages folder, and you can select iris.py from the sidebar in your browser.
